>>128364366
>Maybe with the 6 tournaments and the stat-padding that permits, 10 tournaments is too low for dai-yokozuna discussion ... There's only 18 total yokozuna with 10+ championships
Daiyokozuna doesn't mean 10 yusho. That's some weird Anglosphere concept; the Japanese do not reference it.
Daiyokozuna has historically been used to mean any yokozuna who was/is considered great, irrespective of anything else - for example, Tanikaze is considered a daiyokozuna despite the concept of 'winning' a basho not existing in his time.

The 10-yusho thing also ignores the historically evolving purpose of the yokozuna, which in its early days often was used to celebrate an ozeki who had been very good for a long time (who the House of Yoshida Tsukasa liked). If we count exclusively yusho following yokozuna promotion, Tanikaze had 3. If we count all career yusho, he had 21. Doing this leads to bizarre interpretations, like saying that the greatest yokozuna of all time by career win%, Umegatani I, can't be a daiyokozuna because he had 0 yusho at yokozuna.

I always advice new players to start with rook and pawn endings, get the philidor, lucena, and saavedra positions. Games at a very low level tend to end with those configurations so you will already have the upper foot there.

Once you can develop a keen eye for tactics and overall understand the spirit of any given position, you can start learning the basics of each opening and try to develop and fully study both a 1.d4 and a 1.e4 one, so you can have a varied repertory.

t. FIDE Master

That red bit is the Leki Trigger Shark system's release button. There are three kinds of straps: the old school, new, and quick release straps. There is nothing wrong with the old straps, Julia Simon uses it, but many think the new straps are better for skiing and all xc skiers use them. The down side is the new straps are slower to take off and put on at the shooting range. The solution is quick release straps. The bad thing about quick release is that the strap remains areound your glove while shooting, and some atheletes think it's unstable and it's better to shoot with just your gloves on, which means you have to use either the old or new straps. The choise of strap is really down to personal preference.
